JOHANNESBURG - Media24 has agreed to pay a R14-million admission of guilt settlement, for price-fixing and fixing of trade conditions. The media giant is one of 28 media companies that were referred to the Competition Commission Tribunal for prosecution. It follows a 2011 investigation which found the companies agreed to offer similar discounts and payment terms to ad agencies that placed advertisements with members of the Media Credit Co-Ordinators (MCC). READ:Â Competition Commission unveils school uniform proposal MCC-accredited agencies were offered a 16.5 percent discount, while non-members were offered 15 percent. Other companies that have come to settlement agreements with the Commission are Caxton & CTP Publishers, which paid about R5.8-million, Independent Media, which pay R2.2-million, and DStv Media Sales which paid R22.2-million). The Tribunal is considering prosecuting the other companies, who could be fined up to 10 percent of their annual turnover if found guilty of collusion. eNCA